  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper CLI (fetchers → filters → SQLite store → notify), not a React/JS app, so the \"unnecessary re-renders\" category doesn't apply — I focused on the equivalent hotspots: query patterns, redundant computation, caching, and memory. Four concrete, verified issues:\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the fetched batch, it runs a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With boards like Microsoft/Amazon returning thousands of postings, that's **2N sequential SQLite round trips** per run instead of a handful of batched statements.\n\n```python\n# store.py — batch lookup + executemany instead of per-row execute()\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed = [], []\n    to_insert, to_update, to_touch = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            to_insert.append(row)\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            to_update.append(row)\n        else:\n            to_touch.append({\"key\": job.key, \"now\": now})\n\n    if to_insert:\n        self.conn.executemany(\n            \"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n                 location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n                 content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n               VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n                 :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,\n                 :content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        self.conn.executemany(\n            \"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n                 department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type,\n                 posted_at=:posted_at, salary_range=:salary_range,\n                 content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now\n               WHERE key=:key\"\"\", to_update)\n    if to_touch:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", to_touch)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nOne SELECT for the whole batch + three bulk `executemany` calls, down from thousands of individual statements.\n\n### 2. Redundant regex compilation — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **every single call** — recompiling the same keyword patterns from scratch for every one of the thousands of fetched jobs (O(jobs × keywords) compilations instead of O(keywords)).\n\n```python\n# filters.py — compile once, reuse across all jobs\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations:\n        loc = job.location.lower()\n        if not any(l.lower() in loc for l in locations):\n            return False\n    if cutoff is not None:\n        dt = job.posted_dt\n        if dt is not None and dt < cutoff:\n            return False\n    return True\n\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n### 3. Missing index — `store.py:111-119` (`added_since`)\n\n`agent.py db-new` runs `SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title` on every scan. There's an index on `company` but none on `first_seen`, so this is a full table scan + filesort that gets slower as `jobs.db` accumulates history across runs.\n\n```python\n# store.py — add to _SCHEMA (CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS is idempotent, no migration needed)\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n### 4. Unnecessary memory retention — `Job.raw` (`models.py:52`, `fetchers.py`)\n\nEvery parsed `Job` carries the full source payload in `raw`. I checked — it's **never read anywhere** except being popped inside `to_row()` right before the DB write:\n\n```\n$ grep -rn \"\\.raw\\b\" --include=\"*.py\" .\n(no results)\n```\n\nFor sources like Lever/Ashby/Workable/Workday, `raw=j`/`raw=p` stores the *entire* API object (some ATSs embed full HTML job descriptions in these), multiplied by every posting on boards with thousands of roles — all held in memory for the whole run for a field that's write-only dead weight. Since Google/Amazon/Meta/D.E.Shaw/Two Sigma fetchers already trim `raw` to `{\"id\": ...}`, apply the same pattern everywhere, or drop the field entirely:\n\n```python\n# fetchers.py — e.g. parse_lever, parse_ashby, parse_workable, fetch_workday\nraw={\"id\": j[\"id\"]},   # instead of raw=j / raw=p\n```\n\n---\n\n**Not applicable / already fine:**\n- No React/frontend code in this repo — the re-render category doesn't apply.\n- `fetch_all` (fetchers.py:767-788) already does bounded concurrent fetching (`asyncio.Semaphore`) with per-source failure isolation — no fix needed there.\n- Pagination loops (Microsoft/Amazon/Netflix/Google/Two Sigma/Optiver) already early-exit on the first page with no fresh IDs — reasonable given these are rate-limit-sensitive external APIs, not a hot path worth further caching.\n\nWant me to implement these four fixes directly?\n",
